  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "This is a classic and yet-to-be-resolved issue in the AI literature (Gunning et al. 2019; Doshi-Velez and Kim 2017).",
    "We propose to address the explicability issue under the AI polling paradigm by bolstering existing disclosure standards.",
    "We focus on disclosure standards post-sampling, meaning we do not address issues of transparency in the design and administration of survey instruments, or in the generation of the underlying samples.",
    "These features are generally already well addressed by the major industry associations to which pollsters apply for membership, such as the Market Research Society and the British Polling Council in the UK, or the American Association of Public Opinion Research in the US.",
    "Moreover, to the extent that AI polling brings about novel ways of collecting samples beyond traditional surveying, which are not addressed by the aforementioned institutions-such as the generation of synthetic respondents, the mass scraping of digital trace data, or the linkage of multiple databases-these are only relevant if they can be shown to consistently and directly lead to incorrect estimation of preferences."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "This is a classic and yet-to-be-resolved issue in the AI literature (Gunning et al. 2019; Doshi-Velez and Kim 2017)."
  ]
}